<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Accounts body chief calls for audits shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Auditors should be seen to act more independently of company executives and
public-sector bodies, the chairman of the Accounts Commission of Scotland
said yesterday.
Mr Ian Percy, who is also a senior partner with accountants Grant Thornton,
called for a shake-up in the reporting structures of public and
private-sector auditing in a speech to the conference of the Chartered
Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy.
'The auditor is becoming the tool of the finance officer,' he said after his
speech yesterday. 'There must be mechanisms to ensure that they are auditing
the finance function.'
Mr Percy called for the adoption by public-sector bodies of the
recommendations of the Cadbury committee on the financial aspects of
corporate governance, which was originally aimed at quoted companies.
He said that councils and other public-sector organisations should create
audit committees to improve effectiveness and reporting on financial
matters. Mr Percy called for greater independence of regulation, with the
need for a body separated from the professional accountancy bodies, and with
lay membership to set standards and ethics and to discipline firms.
He said accountancy firms should respond to the perceived threat to
objectivity when auditors provide other services to their clients.
Company audit committees should approve any non-audit work undertaken by the
auditor, he said, while the accountancy firm's audit engagement partner
should not be pressured into cross-selling other services to the client.
Mr Percy also criticised the proposed merger of the UK's six principal
professional accountancy bodies as 'monopolistic'.
In an effort to boost personal responsibility, Mr Percy said the engagement
partner in an accountancy firm should be prepared to sign the audit report
in a company's accounts in his or her own name rather than in the name of
the firm.
Accountancy column, Page 14
</TEXT>
