<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Gooda admission on policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Profits reported in the 1980s by the Gooda Walker agency's syndicate 290
were largely earned by 'time-and-distance' insurance policies, Mr Derek
Walker, the former Gooda Walker chairman, admitted in the High Court
yesterday.
However, he denied he had traded in these policies in an attempt to attract
new Lloyd's Names to his syndicate and so expand his business.
Giving evidence in the High Court action brought against the agency by more
than 3,000 Names, Mr Walker agreed with Mr Geoffrey Vos QC that his dealing
in the policies had helped the spectacular growth of syndicate 290 in the
1980s.
Time-and-distance policies are a form of reinsurance to allow syndicates to
manage reserves against claims several years after the start of policies.
Mr Walker agreed that their use had boosted the syndicates' reported profits
in 1981 to Pounds 2.5m from a Pounds 700,000 loss on all other business. In
1987 they took a Pounds 2.4m profit up to Pounds 8.1m, he agreed.
The use of such policies by syndicate 290 had come as a surprise in parts of
the Lloyd's market and had only been clearly disclosed in 1987, Mr Vos said.
Mr Walker replied that the time-and-distance dealings had been disclosed to
auditors preparing the syndicate's accounts.
Earlier, Mr Walker denied he had been driven to build up syndicate 290 to
prove his ability to the market following his Old Bailey trial in 1981 when
he was accused of conspiracy and eventually acquitted.
Mr Vos asked him whether he had been aware that Mr Peter Green, then Lloyd's
chairman, had opposed his return to the insurance market following his
trial. Mr Walker said he had been unaware of this. The case continues on
Monday.
</TEXT>
