<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Broadcast law overhaul urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Louis Sherwood, chairman of HTV, the ITV company for Wales and the west
country, will tell shareholders tomorrow that there is an urgent need for a
new broadcasting act.
Mr Sherwood intends to use the platform of the company's annual general
meeting to warn that there are so many unresolved problems arising from the
1990 Broadcasting Act that only comprehensive legislation will do.
The HTV chairman believes the issues range from the Channel 4 campaign to
rid itself of the 'safety net', which will probably mean a Pounds 50m
payment to ITV this year, to ownership rules for ITV, and whether British
Telecommunications should have the freedom to be a broadcaster.
Other problems include future ownership of Independent Television News; the
extent to which the regulator, the Independent Television Commission, can
dictate programme schedules; and whether existing programme subsidies for
the smallest ITV companies should continue.
HTV last year opposed the change in the takeover rules that enabled Carlton
to take over Central; Granada to take over London Weekend; and MAI, the
company that controls Meridian, to swallow Anglia Television. HTV believes
little has been achieved as a result, although the deals cost Pounds 50m in
banking and legal fees - worth 100 hours of drama.
Mr Sherwood is expected to denounce what he believes are two myths that have
gained growing support. They are that ITV needs to have big companies to
export programmes around the world, and that television should be treated
like any other sector in competition terms.
The HTV chairman will tell shareholders he knows of no country in the
developed world that does not have special rules for television.
There is a growing feeling in government that a new broadcasting act is
becoming more necessary.
The eventual form will probably depend on what decisions are taken on the
future of the BBC and cross-media ownership rules.
</TEXT>
