<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Housing reforms to go ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to press ahead with changes in housing policy designed to
prevent 'queue-jumping' by homeless lone parents.
This emerged last night after the Earl of Arran, junior environment
minister, accused pressure groups of mounting 'a misleading and alarmist
campaign' against the government's proposals.
Pregnant teenagers, single parents and other vulnerable categories will no
longer be guaranteed speedy access to the permanent tenancy of a house or
flat.
Instead they will be offered temporary accommodation, with guaranteed tenure
of at least six months, while their housing needs are assessed along with
those of other families already on waiting lists.
Lord Arran assured the lords that a 'safety net' would be kept in place for
all those who are classified as statutorily homeless. He said the government
would make a statement next month outlining its response to the
representations made about the new policy.
Legislation to implement it is expected to be introduced in the new
parliamentary session due to open in November.
Baroness Hollis of Heigham, speaking from the Labour front bench, said the
action taken by the government to force up the rents charged by local
authorities and housing associations had contributed to the increase in
homelessness.
She called for the receipts from the sale of council houses to be made
available to provide affordable accommodation for the homeless.
</TEXT>
