<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / TUC welcomes 'devastating blow'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British unions were delighted at yesterday's ruling by the European Court of
Justice. 'This is a devastating blow for the British government,' said Mr
John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress.
'The right of workers to be consulted over redundancies and transfer of
undertakings is a key element of European social policy - one on which the
government are now obliged to legislate.'
Mr Jack Dromey, national officer for the TGWU general union, described the
verdict as 'a landmark decision'.
He added: 'The days of buying and selling workers without their voice being
heard are over. British workers will now enjoy the same protection as
workers in the rest of Europe. The government will have to pay out millions
to tens of thousands of workers.'
But Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, said last night no new employment
compensation cases would arise from the ruling and said that claims from
Opposition spokesmen and union leaders that many 'so-called illegally
sacked' workers would have be eligible were 'outrageous'.
He said the only new element that arose was over consultation - that in
future cases of privatisation employers would be compelled to consult all
their employees, not only recognised unions.
Mr Dromey claimed that the British government would now 'have to legislate
to enshrine for the first time in British law the human rights to
consultation and trade union recognition'. He claimed that 'any attempt by
an employer to derecognise a union will be challenged by our union.'
Lawyers said yesterday that thousands of public-sector workers who lost
their jobs or faced worse employment conditions following privatisation or
the contracting-out of public services could now sue the government for
compensation.
They said workers who could show they suffered loss from the government's
failure to implement important areas of the European acquired rights
directive would be entitled to sue for compensation on the basis of a
European Court decision in 1991 involving Italian workers.
In this instance, called the Francovich case, the court ruled that
individuals had a right to damages where they suffered loss through a
state's failure to implement European Union law.
The TUC has asked the labour academic Lord Wedderburn to present a
considered legal judgment, which will be published shortly.
Five unions - the TGWU, the Unison public service union, the GMB general
union, NUCPS civil service union and the NIPSA Northern Ireland civil
service union - have issued 128 writs against the government covering more
than a thousand public-sector workers in local government, the National
Health Service and government employment, claiming retrospective
compensation for loss of earnings when their jobs were moved into the
private sector.
The TUC hopes to negotiate a settlement with the government over
compensation for as many as 60,000 workers affected rather than pursue
individual cases through the courts, which would be expensive and
time-consuming.
Mr Dromey said the unions had no dispute with contractors and other
employers involved in transfers of employment to the private sector.
</TEXT>
<XX>
