<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Hauliers warn on Channel tunnel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel risks a crisis of confidence among customers if it has further
problems with its freight shuttle service through the Channel tunnel, the
Road Haulage Association warned yesterday, Jimmy Burns and Charles Batchelor
write.
The warning came after the temporary suspension of a train service yesterday
because of technical problems - the second such incidence in 11 days.
Mr Sydney Balgarnie of the association said: 'If they haven't got this
problem cracked soon, there is going to be trouble. People do not want to
get stranded in the tunnel. People want reliability and if they don't get it
they will use the ferries instead.'
Eurotunnel said the two incidents were unrelated although both involved
warning lights that signalled non-existent faults. In one the warning
indicated that the ramps used by trucks driving on to the shuttles were
extended, while in the second a light warned that a train's anti-skid
mechanism was not working.
In yesterday's incident drivers of lorries travelling on the shuttles were
evacuated from the tunnel.
Mr John Noulton, Eurotunnel's public-affairs director, said: 'These were
irritations. It is what you would expect at this stage of introducing a new
railway. The trains could have continued normally but at this stage of the
system our procedures are very strict and we followed them to the letter.'
Eurotunnel has been operating for just over two weeks and has run about 200
trains through the tunnel.
</TEXT>
