<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / C&amp;G studies ways to beat takeover ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Closing Cheltenham and Gloucester Building Society to new members was one of
the boldest moves suggested yesterday by which the society could get round
the High Court judgment against the takeover by Lloyds Bank.
Once the society had closed, it would simply have to wait until all its
members had acquired at least two years' standing. But, although that would
be a theoretically elegant conclusion, it would be likely to disrupt the
original takeover timetable. Halting the growth of the society would also
make it less attractive to Lloyds.
The court ruling may well make it hardest for banks to take over the most
attractive societies because those that are growing fastest will have the
highest proportions of new members to whom payments are not allowed to be
made.
C&amp;G is one of the fastest-growing of all societies - as indicated by the
fact that 27 per cent of its members are of less than two years' standing. A
society with only a small proportion of new members is likely to be moribund
and small.
A possibility canvassed as an alternative to a cash bid was that Lloyds
could make payments of preference shares as an alternative to cash. However,
any easy exchange of such shares for cash could make such a scheme illegal.
The society may consider other alternatives to closing itself to new
members:
Giving members' of less than two years' standing some value for the
surrender of their voting rights. Provided that there was no vote against
the takeover from these investors, Lloyds' bid could well pass the the
voting thresholds.
This possibility is raised by Sir Donald Nicholls' ruling that a third party
can make payments to non-voting members of a society. Lloyds might be able
to make payments to people who chose to become non-members using this
provision.
Dividing the Pounds 1.8m among those of two years' standing. Mr Andrew
Longhurst, C&amp;G chief executive, who has been keen to show the widespread
benefits of the Lloyds' offer, discounted this possibility last night.
However, it could be used if no alternative was found.
Because only a 50 per cent majority of those eligible to vote is required,
the society could well gain such a majority from the 73 per cent whom it was
paying. The problem would be if members of under two years' standing voted
against.
C&amp;G takeover, Page 10
</TEXT>
