<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Eurotunnel is warned of customer crisis of confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eurotunnel risks a crisis of confidence among customers if it has further
problems with its freight shuttle service through the Channel tunnel, the
Road Haulage Association warned yesterday.
Mr Sydney Balgarnie, the association's spokesman, said: 'If they haven't got
this problem cracked soon, there is going to be trouble. People do not want
to get stranded in the tunnel. People want reliability, and if they don't
get it they will use the ferries instead.'
His comments came after yesterday's incident involving the temporary
suspension of a train service because of technical problems - the second
such incident in 11 days. Eurotunnel said the two incidents were unrelated
though both involved warning lights that signalled non-existent faults.
In one instance the warning indicated that the ramps used by trucks driving
on to the shuttles were extended, while in the second a light warned that a
train's anti-skid mechanism was not working.
In the second incident, drivers of lorries travelling on the shuttles were
evacuated from the tunnel.
Mr John Noulton, Eurotunnel's public affairs director, said: 'These were
irritations. It is what you would expect at this stage of introducing a new
railway. The trains could have continued normally, but at this stage of the
system our procedures are very strict and we followed them to the letter.'
Eurotunnel has been operating for just over two weeks and has run about 200
trains through the tunnel.
Mr John Chapman, Eurotunnel freight sales manager, said the incidents 'had
no safety implications at all'. No drivers were in danger.
Mr Balgarnie said that any breakdown in the tunnel had a psychological
effect which would intensify once a full service was running.
Last month Eurotunnel launched a highly-discounted promotion service for
selected transport companies with the aim of attracting hauliers who
normally use ferry services.
</TEXT>
