   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US Navy moved yesterday to safeguard its shipyards by announcing that it
would split contracts evenly for six Dollars 1bn Aegis destroyers between
two yards without competing bids, Reuter reports from Washington.
Navy Secretary John Dalton called the radical departure from competition for
such contracts 'a smart business strategy. . . to maintain a healthy
industrial base for the surface combatants that will lead the Navy into the
21st century'.
The yards are Ingalls, a unit of Litton Industries in Pascagoula,
Mississippi, and Bath Iron Works which is a private shipyard in Bath, Maine.
Each company has previously built Aegis guided missile destroyers. The
contracts will be awarded this year and next.
