<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Shipping line controls sought
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shipping lines should not be allowed to fix prices for the land leg of
long-haul deliveries, the European Commission said yesterday. A report by Mr
Karel Van Miert, competition commissioner, says that shipping 'conferences'
 -powerful agreements between shipping lines - would be contravening
competition rules if they agreed to fix prices on road or rail transport to
and from ports. At present, shipping conferences have a bloc exemption from
competition rules on the port-to-port leg of journeys, allowing them to fix
common rates. They argue that they be unprofitable, otherwise. However, big
EU exporters say the shipping lines are behaving as an illegal cartel and
imposing exorbitant prices. The report, approved by the Commission
yesterday, will be presented to transport ministers at next week's council
meeting.
</TEXT>
