<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / EU poll issues that have guided Twelve campaigns: France
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Voting Sunday. The main French right- and left-wing parties and groupings
favour political and monetary union, although some of the electorate has
been showing increasing scepticism. Both left and right have had their
support eaten away by dissidents within their own camp.
On the right, the anti-Maastricht list of dissident conservatives has seen
support running unexpectedly high at 7-9 per cent. The Socialist list, led
by Mr Michel Rocard, has faced even harder competition. First, from that led
by Mr Bernard Tapie, nominally an ally and a declared European federalist,
but whose only policy is to make youth unemployment illegal. Second, from
the 'Bosnia' list led by Mr Leon Schwartzenberg campaigning for an end to
the Bosnian Moslems arms embargo. In some polls it has scored the 5 per cent
minimum needed to win Euro-seats in France.
LIKELY RESULT: Latest polls give the UDF-RPR list of the governing coalition
31-32 per cent. Socialists expected to do badly, with one poll putting
support as low as 13.5 per cent, which would be a disastrous start to Mr
Rocard's campaign for the presidency next year. The Communists and National
Front have polled around 7 and 10 per cent respectively.
</TEXT>
