<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JUN 94 / Sharp rise in output increases hopes of recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Tory party was given a boost ahead of today's European elections as
sharp rises in industrial production and factory output in April raised
hopes that the UK recovery was gaining strength.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, said the production figures were 'the best
news on the economy so far this year. Growth is stronger and spread wider'.
His upbeat assessment, which was echoed yesterday by the Treasury's monthly
monetary report, suggests that the recent downward trend in UK interest
rates has ended.
The report was issued as Mr Clarke met Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank
of England, for their monthly monetary talks. Although the details of the
meeting are not released for six weeks, the Treasury report, coupled with
the production figures, left most City analysts convinced that the
authorities are unlikely to change the base rates from their present level
of 5 1/4 per cent.
UK money markets currently assume that the Bank will raise interest rates to
about 6 per cent by the end of the year as stronger growth fuels
inflationary pressures. However, the Treasury report hinted that the
chancellor was unlikely to endorse any attempt by the Bank to push rates up
in the short term.
Although the report does not provide policy prescriptions, it noted that
inflation was at its lowest level in April since 1967. It also pointed out
that in spite of the recent rise in average earnings, wage settlements
remained broadly unchanged.
The report's upbeat presentation of the UK recovery suggested little need
for a fiscal stimulus in spite of recent tax rises. 'The latest monthly
indicators (are) consistent with continuing recovery.'
April's figures for industrial production and manufacturing output appeared
to underline the strength of the UK economic recovery. Seasonally adjusted,
the indicators showed month-on-month rises of 1.6 per cent and 1.1 per cent
respectively.
That was well above market expectations, which had centred on a rise of
about 0.5 per cent for production and output.
While the figures were boosted by some one-off factors, such as a fuel
output, there were signs of strength in such key industries as engineering.
April's oil and gas output passed the previous monthly record, set in May
1987.
Analysts were encouraged by the breakdown of the figures, showing production
of investment goods growing faster than that of consumer goods. In the past,
consumer-led UK recoveries have quickly led to balance-of-payment
constraints.
Output beats hopes, Page 13
</TEXT>
