<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / UK Company News: VideoLogic joining market valued at up to
Pounds 83.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VideoLogic, the Hertfordshire-based multimedia company, is to be demerged
from its parent, Avesco, the broadcasting services company, and floated on
the Stock Exchange via a placing and offer valuing the company at between
Pounds 70.5m and Pounds 83.9m.
Avesco shareholders will receive one VideoLogic share for each Avesco share.
They will also have a preferential opportunity to participate in the
placing, which is expected to raise Pounds 21.5m of new money before
expenses.
Some Pounds 13m will be available to VideoLogic to fund research and
development into improved systems for full motion video on personal computer
displays.
Yesterday, Mr Richard Murray, Avesco chairman, said VideoLogic had been
transformed beyond recognition since it was acquired in 1989 and its
potential could best be exploited through a separate listing.
At the same time, Avesco announced results for the year to March 31, showing
revenues 4 per cent down at Pounds 22.5m (Pounds 23.4m) while losses rose
from Pounds 1.3m to Pounds 7.2m. Losses per share were 9p (2.2p) and the
dividend is passed. VideoLogic had sales of Pounds 9m and lost Pounds 5.6m.
Its results over the past three years have been hit by VideoLogic's
requirements for research funding, totalling almost Pounds 10m. Following
the demerger, Avesco is expected to have sales of Pounds 15m with pre-tax
profits initially of about Pounds 1m. The net asset value of the company
following the demerger will be about 18.5p a share.
The demerged VideoLogic's shares have not been priced. Warburgs, which is
underwriting the placing, will determine a price of between 55p and 70p
through book building.
The difference between the new money to be raised and available to the
company will be accounted for by expenses, repayment of borrowings and the
repayment of debt to Avesco.
Mr Derek Maclaren, VideoLogic chairman, and Mr Anthony Maclaren, managing
director, are entitled to a bonus from Avesco on demerger, but have agreed
to invest an aggregate Pounds 1.2m in VideoLogic shares, representing about
half the bonus after deducting Pounds 250,000 each and making allowance for
taxation.
Dealing in the shares will start on July 6.
Yesterday Avesco's shares fell 12p to 82p.
</TEXT>
