<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / French Groupe Schneider chairman released on bail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
An 11-night stay in a Brussels prison ended last night for one of France's
best known industrialists when Mr Didier Pineau-Valencienne, chairman of
Groupe Schneider, was released on bail.
Mr Pineau-Valencienne left Brussel's Forest prison at 7pm after Mr Jean
Claude Van Espen, the Belgian prosecuting judge in charge of the case, was
satisfied that there was no longer any reason to detain him.
The chairman of Schneider, one of Europe's largest electrical engineering
groups, was arrested two weeks ago on charges of fraud, embezzlement and
falsification of accounts. That followed an investigation prompted by
complaints from minority shareholders of two Belgian subsidiaries of
Schneider: Cofimines and Cofibel.
Mr Valentino Foti, an Italian businessman arrested on similar charges,
remained imprisoned in Brussels last night. According to his lawyer, he is
unlikely to be released until the Italian authorities have completed their
investigations on behalf of the Belgian prosecutors or until his appeal is
heard in Belgium.
Mr Pineau-Valencienne, who returned to Paris, was released on bail of BFr15m
(Pounds 291,000). He was also ordered by the judge to present himself
whenever required to the judicial authorities and to do nothing that might
interfere with the investigation.
The Belgian authorities came under intense political pressure to hasten Mr
Pineau-Valencienne's release after his arrest two weeks ago caused uproar in
the French media and within the business community. The arrest prompted
France's prime minister Edouard Balladur to phone his Belgian counterpart,
Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, while Mr Alain Juppe, France's foreign minister,
telephoned his opposite number, Mr Willy Claes.
Sources close to the case say the French executive met Mr Van Espen
yesterday afternoon, after further questioning by investigators recently
returned from France and Switzerland.
The accusations facing Schneider centre on its treatment of Cofibel and
Cofimines and a bid, launched in 1992, to buy out minority shareholders in
the two subsidiaries. Belgian prosecutors say there were irregularities in
the offer.
Mr Van Espen will now continue his investigation of the minority
shareholders' complaints on the basis of what the searches in France, Italy
and Switzerland have uncovered. Last week French and Belgian police searched
the Paris headquarters of Schneider.
The completed report will be presented to the Belgian prosecutors' office.
It will then be up to an advisory court to decide whether to throw out the
case or to refer it to the criminal court.
</TEXT>
