<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / Plans to alter APR formula are attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Office of Fair Trading's proposal to change the way in which annual
percentage rates are calculated is one of the most controversial aspects of
yesterday's report on the Consumer Credit Act.
The Consumers' Association said yesterday that the changes would 'weaken
consumer protection and confuse consumers.'
The OFT recommended that APRs on credit and store cards should be based only
on the interest-charge element of the total charge for credit, with
'separate and bold' disclosure of fees and any other fixed charges.
This change, which would require an amendment to the European Union
directive on APRs, would help consumers understand the marginal cost of
using one existing credit facility over another, said the OFT.
The Consumers' Association said that the proposal 'flies in the face of the
whole purpose of the APR' since it would prevent the APR from being the
benchmark for comparison of all types of credit.
As an interim measure to improve the consistency of APRs, the OFT said
calculations of APRs for advertising purposes should be based on an
outstanding credit card balance of Pounds 500 - close to the average balance
on credit cards - rather than the current Pounds 1,000.
The OFT also recommended that mortgage lenders quote separate APR figures
for the initial period of a fixed or discounted rate mortgage and for the
period after it has ended. Lenders often use the initial rate as the basis
for quoting the APR on the entire life of the loan.
This was criticised by the Consumers' Association as adding to confusion.
The Council of Mortgage Lenders said it would improve the unsatisfactory
position, although it doubted whether the APR was sufficiently understood to
make it a useful contributor to consumer protection.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said the concern that
consumers had little understanding of APRs was 'unnecessarily negative'.
Research commissioned by the OFT into consumers' understanding of APRs found
that fewer than half those questioned correctly identified its meaning and
30 per cent said they had considered the APR when looking for credit and
loan arrangements.
</TEXT>
