<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / Two buy-out teams considering coal bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two management buy-out teams announced yesterday they were considering plans
to bid for parts of British Coal. Their announcement came as the government
disclosed that 25 companies had qualified to bid for the five UK regions on
offer.
Mr Bob Siddall, director of opencast operations, and Mr David Brewer, head
of finance, said their company, English Coal, had qualified to bid for the
three regions incorporating England and north Wales.
Mr Alan Houghton, director of the central north region comprising the
Yorkshire pits, is heading Northern Coal, a company which has qualified to
bid for the region he runs.
A third buy-out team is expected to announce its plans today. Mr Bryan
Riddleston, regional director for the South Wales opencast region, is
thought to be leading a potential bid for his area.
National Power and PowerGen, the main electricity generators, are thought to
be among the other 22 companies which have qualified. Analysts believe it is
extremely unlikely they will make a bid, but that they want to look at the
businesses of future suppliers.
Both companies are thought to have paid the Pounds 75,000 necessary to
qualify in all five coal regions.
Mr Keith Palmer, managing director of NM Rothschild, the merchant bank
advising the government on privatisation, would not say yesterday which
companies had qualified to bid.
However he said that of the 33 which had applied, 25 had qualified to bid
for one or more of the regions. Several others among the 33 had qualified
for one or more of the six stand-alone mines. A small, unspecified number of
the 33 had failed to meet technical or financial criteria, Mr Palmer said.
The qualifying companies were yesterday sent information covering the areas
or pits in which they are interested.
The companies will have access to the areas or pits in which they are
interested and a data room, and will be able to visit British Coal sites.
Bids are due in mid September. English Coal, which is advised by Coopers &amp;
Lybrand, the consultancy firm, said it had qualified as a prospective bidder
for five of the six stand-alone pits: Goldthorpe, Thorne, Annesley/Bentinck,
Ellington and Kiveton.
English Coal and Northern Coal said employees and management would be given
the chance to participate in the ownership and profits of their businesses
if the bids succeeded.
