<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / ICI chief warns banks against short-termism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pressure from shareholders could hamper banks' efforts to build supportive
long-term relationships with large companies, Sir Denys Henderson, chairman
of Imperial Chemical Industries, warned yesterday.
Speaking in London at the International Monetary Conference, a meeting of
senior executives from 103 large banks, Sir Denys said that banks should
take a 'long-term supportive' stance towards customers.
'I suspect that the pressure on under-performing banks to improve their
shareholder value will grow, which may make even the most tolerant more
critical of clients' performance than in the past,' Sir Denys said.
He added that a long-term supportive stance 'through fair and foul weather
alike' was the normal model in Asia-Pacific, particularly in Japan.
Germany's practice was also close to that of Japan but the tendency was less
prevalent elsewhere.
Sir Denys criticised some banks for being more interested in 'peddling the
deal of the day' rather than preserving objectivity in the advice they
offered to companies on how to improve performance.
He said that while other industries wanted stability to make long-term
investment plans, 'some parts of the banking industry welcome volatility,
which generates excitement and the prospect of large instant gains'. Sir
Denys said that ICI remained 'keenly interested in receiving innovative
advice which will improve our financial performance' but that advisers
should strike a balance between objectivity and keenness to do business.
In a separate discussion on financial centres, Lord Alexander, chairman of
National Westminster Bank, said that London would depend on its 'continuing
capacity to innovate' and form the hub of a global network.
He said there would 'always be the need for a leading centre in the European
time zone, but Madrid, Amsterdam, Paris and Frankfurt all have their own
aspirations' and London's position would be challenged.
Baron Alexandre Lamfalussy, president of the European Monetary Institute,
based in Frankfurt, said the European Monetary Union needed to be based in a
sophisticated financial centre to perform its future role as a monetary
authority.
IMC members, who meet in a financial centre once a year to discuss matters
affecting the international banking industry, were received last night at
Buckingham Palace by the Queen and the Duke of Edinburgh.
Better balance for loan arrangers, Page 23
</TEXT>
