<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / OECD fuels row on minimum pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The OECD's report on job creation saw each of the three main parties
claiming support for its own strategy. First, Mr Major was joined by
ministers saying the report endorsed their emphasis on deregulated and
flexible markets.
The prime minister said on LBC radio that it was 'a great setback for Labour
that independent experts have looked at what they wish to do and said it is
nonsense'.
He added that Labour wanted to 'interrupt markets and try to regulate them,
and the whole thrust of the report is in precisely the opposite direction'.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said the conclusions had
exposed Labour's commitment to a minimum wage as a recipe for job
destruction.
But Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, led an opposition counter-attack
based on the OECD's call for flexible markets to be balanced by greater
emphasis on education and training.
Mr John Prescott, shadow employment secretary, said the Tories had
'deliberately misrepresented' the report to hide the 'catastrophic economic
failure' of deregulation.
He said the Tories had created a 'low-skill, low-investment, low-pay
economy' which could not protect against 'the onslaught of cheap competition
from low-wage economies'.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, said the report supported the government's
argument that job creation depends on supply-side reforms focusing on
flexible labour markets.
'These policies have helped us to get unemployment down by nearly 300,000
from its peak, while it has continued to rise elsewhere in Europe,' he said.
Labour said the report left open the option of a 'responsible' minimum wage,
even though it recommends abolition in countries which already have such
legislation. The party pointed to a passage suggesting that the 'adverse
employment effects' could be minimised by indexation of the minimum wage to
prices rather than earnings.
Mr Alan Beith, Liberal Democrat treasury spokesman, said the report was 'a
direct criticism of the government's policies'. Mr Beith, who opposes a
national minimum wage, called for decentralisation of wage bargaining and
public transport and housing reforms to raise labour market flexibility.
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
