FT  08 JUN 94 / Jobs shed in Tory seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Why pick today?'
This was the reaction of Mr Robert Sturdy, Conservative candidate for the
Cambridgeshire Euro-seat, to yesterday's announcement by Anglian Water that
it is to shed up to 900 jobs within three years. It must have been shared by
Conservatives throughout the constituency.
The announcement coincided with news from the Hampshire by-election town of
Eastleigh, which the Liberal Democrats are expected to win from the
Conservatives, that Pirelli, the cable maker, is to axe 136 jobs.
Mr Sturdy, standing in a seat the Tories should win and which contains Mr
John Major's parliamentary constituency, said he was worried about the
timing of Anglian Water's announcement, which came as the company announced
pre-tax profits for the year to the end of March of Pounds 132.2m.
'Why have they decided to say something today when the job losses are over
two to three years?' he said. 'One wonders if it is political. It makes me
wonder.'
Anglian said almost all the job cuts would be among administrative workers -
it is to close one of its two headquarters buildings, one of which is in
Huntingdon, the other in Cambridge.
At Eastleigh, Mr Stephen Reid, the Conservative candidate, said Pirelli's
decision was 'a fact of life'.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, said the job losses were
'likely to be as a direct result of the government's failure to invest in
training and infrastructure'.
Pirelli said the timing of the announcement had nothing to do with the
by-election. 'That is incidental to the running of our business,' it said.
'But we do expect some possible criticism.'
Anglian results, Page 25
