<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / New fizz on the box
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It's not the real thing. But J. Sainsbury has decided the television
advertisement for its new cola will go better with a few American icons
thrown in.
Unabashed by complaints last month from a certain well-known world market
leader, which forced Sainsbury to change the design on the outside of the
can, the food retailer is to run an advert which rummages through American
cultural baggage in search of increased sales.
A bemused employee watches an American basketball player in a limousine as
it pulls up outside a Sainsbury's superstore, whose car park is full of
American cars.
The slogan promises that Classic Cola - made from concentrate supplied by
Cott, the Canadian soft-drinks manufacturer - delivers a 'classic American
taste at a Sainsbury's price'.
The commercial shows Classic Cola's new packaging, although cans with this
design will not go on sale until late July. Sainsbury altered the typography
of the design - white italic lettering on a red background - after Coca-Cola
complained that its resemblance to Coca-Cola's cans might confuse customers.
Mr Ivor Hunt, Sainsbury's marketing director, denied that the advertisement
was a response to heavy advertising by Coca-Cola, and said the advert - to
coincide with the time of year when soft drink sales are highest - had been
budgeted for since Classic Cola was launched.
'It is a logical and necessary stage in the post-launch development of the
brand,' he said. 'It is much better to get the product in (the stores) and
make sure the logistics are in place before starting the advertising.'
The Classic Cola advert was developed by the creative consultancy Fourhead.
Sainsbury's usual agency, Abbott Mead Vickers BBDO, faced a potential
conflict of interest with another client - Pepsi.
</TEXT>
