<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / Call to exploit TV superhighway
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK is uniquely placed to take a global stake in 'the biggest commercial
play of the next century' - the development of the information superhighway,
the Royal Television Society heard last night.
Professor David Youlton, chairman of broadcasting technology group Snell and
Wilcox, said the UK could not claim pre-eminence in either
telecommunications or computers but it had 'the world's largest and most
sophisticated knowledge base in the art of the moving image in real time
combined with a deep understanding of all that happens between the
transmitter and the receiver in the home.'
Mr Youlton, who is visiting professor of business studies at Kingston
University in London, praised the BBC Research Department as being the
broadcasting equivalent of Nasa, the US space agency, by producing a
constant stream of spin-off technology.
US technology in this area had been impoverished by the closure or hiving
off of the research laboratories of the US networks.
