<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / World Trade News: BA seeks to enter China air ventures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Airways is among a growing number of large western airlines stepping
up efforts to participate in the modernisation of the fast-expanding Chinese
air transport industry through joint ventures and other partnerships with
Chinese carriers.
BA is already co-operating with China Southern, the Guangzhou-based airline,
and is in talks with Shanghai-based China Eastern Airlines, Mr David Holmes,
BA's director of government and international affairs, said yesterday.
Like other international carriers, BA now sees more promising long-term
opportunities in China than in Russia where its project to start a new
airline called Air Russia has been placed on hold indefinitely.
In contrast to Russia, China offered an administrative framework to conduct
daily business while in Russia it was currently difficult to advance on any
project until the political situation stabilised, Mr Holmes said.
The Civil Aviation Administration of China and Chinese airlines have also
become increasingly conscious of their technical weakness and the urgent
need to improve safety, punctuality and efficiency standards in the face of
explosive domestic air traffic growth which is averaging 20 per cent a year.
This week's crash of a China Northeast Airline's Russian-built Tupolev
Tu-154, in which 160 people died, has added to the urgency of overhauling
the country's aviation system.
It was China's worst air disaster.
China is also keen to commercialise its state-controlled airline industry
and is proposing to sell stakes to foreign investors in its 33 regional
carriers. It has also recently suggested the possibility of listing some of
the bigger carriers on the New York Stock Exchange in an effort to secure
outside financing.
BA is not currently pushing to take a stake in one or more Chinese airlines
but its longer-term ambition is to negotiate a marketing agreement with a
carrier such as Chinese Eastern to co-ordinate services at Beijing airport.
BA, however, recently hosted a visit of Chinese aviation officials to the UK
to discuss the possible way forward for Chinese airline privatisation.
With China Southern, which operates a fleet of Boeing aircraft, BA, which is
also a big Boeing operator, has formed an engineering joint venture. It also
recently sold China Southern some computering services. BA sees pilot
training as another area of possible co-operation with Chinese carriers.
BA, which flies twice a week from London to Beijing and is keen to double
its weekly services, is anxious to establish a stronger foothold in China at
a time when some of its main international competitors are intensifying
co-operation with the Chinese airline industry.
Lufthansa of Germany already operates six flights a week to Beijing and is
involved in a large aircraft maintenance centre in the Chinese capital.
Singapore Airlines has earmarked China as one of its three main growth areas
for the next decade together with India and Vietnam. It has taken a 40 per
cent stake in the company handling ground services at Beijing airport and
another 40 per cent stake in Beijing airport's inflight kitchen group.
Singapore Airline's engineering subsidiary has also invested in a 10 per
cent stake in the Xiamen joint aircraft engineering venture which includes
as partners Cathay Pacific and Japan Air Lines. Its recently formed leasing
company has leased a Boeing 767 to China Southern.
</TEXT>
