<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / Japan's planners upgrade outlook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese government's Economic Planning Agency yesterday slightly
upgraded its outlook, saying the economy remained stagnant overall but
showed emerging bright spots.
The agency's change in tone in its latest monthly report comes a day after
the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development upgraded its
forecast for the Japanese economy, from 0.5 per cent to a still weak 0.8 per
cent growth in gross domestic product this year. Last month, the EPA said
the economy was sluggish, in a record 37 months of decline.
The OECD and EPA changes reflect the gradual impact of previous governments'
four economic stimulation packages, worth Y45,000bn (Pounds 286bn) over 18
months.
The EPA highlighted a smaller-than-expected fall in industrial production in
May as a bright sign. 'It is too early technically to declare the economy
has reached bottom, but my impression is that it has,' said Mr Yoshio
Terasawa, EPA director-general.
This latest EPA survey adds weight to market expectations that the Bank of
Japan's Tankan quarterly study of business confidence, the country's most
authoritative indicator of the short-term economic outlook due out on
Friday, will show a broad improvement.
Recently, the EPA has used more pessimistic language to describe the
economic outlook than most private-sector forecasters, yet at the same time
stuck to an official forecast of 2.4 per cent GDP growth this year, seen by
most private-sector economists as unachievable.
But Mr Hirohisa Fujii, finance minister, said yesterday the government had
to seek to hit the official target by passing this year's budget and
implementing steps to stimulate demand, such as the one-year income tax cut
agreed by the last government.
The budget for the year starting in April, delayed by Japan's internal
political wranglings, is expected to clear parliament this month.
New stimulus packages or monetary measures will be unnecessary, so long as
the budget is passed, said Mr Masaru Hayami, head of the Japan Association
of Corporate Executives. Corporate performance should improve by autumn, in
line with market forecasts that profits will pick up gently this year, after
a four-year decline.
</TEXT>
