<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUN 94 / Information highway comes to a crossroads: Paul Cheeseright
catches up on a Herefordshire experiment in local computing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An experiment in stimulating rural economic development by providing a
community with a package of the latest computer and communications
technology has reached a crossroads.
In the next two weeks, sponsors and local interests running the scheme at
Kington, Herefordshire, will decide the extent to which the project should
become a moneymaking exercise and the extent to which it will meet, often
unorganised, community demands.
What is clear is the idea that simply installing more than Pounds 250,000 of
electronic equipment in the community would itself stimulate rapid economic
development has been disproved.
Decisions over the future of Kington Connected Community Company (KC3), the
company set up to run the project, will be reached after an intricate
diplomatic minuet as the financial sponsors seek to induce KC3 to take the
decisions they would like, without appearing to dictate events. There is
nothing more difficult to deal with than a partnership, sighed one sponsor.
Discussion will be around a new business plan worked out for KC3 by Morton
Hodson, the Worcester consultants, and financed by the Rural Development
Commission, one of the main national sponsors.
Local sponsors include Leominster District Council, which provided KC3 with
a building, and Hereford and Worcestershire Training and Enterprise Council.
The main technical support has come from Apple, which through Rothwell, its
agents, provided 34 computers, and BT, which has fitted Kington into its
ISDN system, giving it state-of-the-art communications.
Mr Russell Brady, Apple's corporate relations officer, said Apple was
'reasonably happy' so far. He went to the heart of what sponsors see as the
Kington problem. 'What is required from Kington is to get some projects
management skills into the community,' he said. 'Management skills have to
be put on top of the enthusiasm and that is up to the community to work
out.'
The Morton Hodson recommendations for Kington are not yet known but their
general drift is fairly clear. They will seek to reconcile, in a business
plan, commercial need and community duty.
'There's got to be a balance,' said Mr Gerald Harris, a Morton Hodson
partner. 'But it's got to work in financial terms.'
The business plan should have been ready last April, but the task was more
complicated than expected. Not only that - Morton Hodson was drawn into
immediate management problems at KC3, he said.
The problem is that KC3 has a lot of gear but no money. At the moment it
does not earn enough to pay staff.
'There are too many machines and not enough bodies to drive them,' said Mr
Phil Pattington, director of technical services at Rothwell.
The orthodox approach to regeneration projects is to put the first 85 per
cent of resources into people and cash, and 15 per cent into gear. At
Kington, it has been the other way round. There are lots of ideas about
using the computers, but not necessarily ideas which produce revenue to keep
the operation going.
The challenge is both to produce revenue and to keep faith with the local
community. The original brief, recalled Mr Miles Swinburne, the KC3 project
manager, was 50-50 community-commercial activity.
'If you start using too much (of the equipment) on the commercial side,
people on the community side cry 'foul',' he said. It is a sign of the
pressures for change already working on KC3 that Mr Swinburne now spends his
time working up outside projects - employment and tourist information
databases for example - and that a new manager has been recruited to run the
KC3 telecentre in the town centre.
'We tried the completely neutral approach of saying 'here we are, what do
you want to do?' But it wasn't focused enough,' Mr Swinburne said.
'We're having to be more proactive, suggesting things beforehand, rather
than later.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Kington Connected Community.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7389 Business Services, NEC.
    P7379 Computer Related
    Services, NEC.
</IN>
