<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets: Brazil surges 8 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Sao Paulo ended 7.9 per cent stronger after heavy trade spurred by
optimism over the government's anti-inflation plan, which includes the
adoption of a new currency, and strong overseas buying. The Bovespa index
surged 2,127 to 29,087. Turnover came to Cr502.4bn.
A broker said many foreign investors rushed to the cash market after the
Bovespa futures index broke the 30,700-point resistance level.
Food, retail, beverage, clothing and state blue chips led the rally.
Analysts said the July 1 introduction of the new currency, the real, is
expected to sharply reduce Brazil's 45 per cent monthly inflation, paving
the way for a surge in consumer spending.
Brokers observed that investor sentiment was also helped by reports at the
weekend that Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, the current economy minister and
a presidential candidate, had seen an improvement in his standing in opinion
polls.
Salomon Brothers, in a recent commentary, noted that the possibility of a
victory in the October elections by the left-wing candidate Mr Luiz Inacio
da Silva could not be ruled out, but placed the possibility of a Cardoso
victory at around 55 per cent.
